@database XZDEC
@master "XZDEC.1"
@remark "manual page source format generated by PolyglotMan v3.2 available at http://polyglotman.sourceforge.net/"
@wordwrap
@tab 8

@node sect0 "Name"
xzdec, lzmadec - Small .xz and .lzma decompressors 
@endnode

@node sect1 "Synopsis"
@{b}xzdec@{ub} [@{i}option@{ui}]...@{i}@{ui} [@{i}file@{ui}]...@{i}@{ui} 
@{b}lzmadec@{ub} [@{i}option@{ui}]...@{i}@{ui} [@{i}file@{ui}]...@{i}@{ui} 
@endnode

@node sect2 "Description"
@{b}xzdec@{ub} is a liblzma-based decompression-only tool for @{b}.xz@{ub} (and only @{b}.xz@{ub}) files. @{b}xzdec@{ub} is intended to work as a drop-in replacement for @{"@{b}xz@{ub}(1)" link %s.%sxz1/main} in the most common situations where a script has been written to use @{b}xz --decompress --stdout@{ub} (and possibly a few other commonly used options) to decompress @{b}.xz@{ub} files. @{b}lzmadec@{ub} is identical to @{b}xzdec@{ub} except that @{b}lzmadec@{ub} supports @{b}.lzma@{ub} files instead of @{b}.xz@{ub} files. To reduce the size of the executable, @{b}xzdec@{ub} doesn't support multithreading or localization, and doesn't read options from @{b}XZ_OPT@{ub} environment variable. @{b}xzdec@{ub} doesn't support displaying intermediate progress information: sending @{b}SIGINFO@{ub} to @{b}xzdec@{ub} does nothing, but sending @{b}SIGUSR1@{ub} terminates the process instead of displaying progress information. 


@endnode

@node sect3 "Options"


· @{b}-d@{ub}, @{b}--decompress@{ub}, @{b}--uncompress@{ub} @{lindent 3}
Ignored for @{"@{b}xz@{ub}(1)" link %s.%sxz1/main} compatibility. @{b}xzdec@{ub} supports only decompression. @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-k@{ub}, @{b}--keep@{ub} @{lindent 3}
Ignored for @{"@{b}xz@{ub}(1)" link %s.%sxz1/main} compatibility. @{b}xzdec@{ub} never creates or removes any files. @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-c@{ub}, @{b}--stdout@{ub}, @{b}--to-stdout@{ub} @{lindent 3}
Ignored for @{"@{b}xz@{ub}(1)" link %s.%sxz1/main} compatibility. @{b}xzdec@{ub} always writes the decompressed data to standard output. @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-M@{ub} @{i}limit@{ui}, @{b}--memory=@{i}limit @{ui}@{ub}@{lindent 3}
Set the memory usage @{i}limit@{ui}. If this option is specified multiple times, the last one takes effect. The @{i}limit@{ui} can be specified in multiple ways: @{lindent 6}
@{lindent 3}

· ·@{lindent 6}
The @{i}limit@{ui} can be an absolute value in bytes. Using an integer suffix like @{b}MiB@{ub} can be useful. Example: @{b}--memory=80MiB@{ub} @{lindent 3}

· ·@{lindent 6}
The @{i}limit@{ui} can be specified as a percentage of physical RAM. Example: @{b}--memory=70%@{ub} @{lindent 3}

· ·@{lindent 6}
The @{i}limit@{ui} can be reset back to its default value by setting it to @{b}0@{ub}. @{lindent 3}

· ·@{lindent 6}
The memory usage limiting can be effectively disabled by setting @{i}limit@{ui} to @{b}max@{ub}. This isn't recommended. It's usually better to use, for example, @{b}--memory=90%@{ub}. @{lindent 3}

@{lindent 0}


· The current @{lindent 3}
@{i}limit@{ui} can be seen near the bottom of the output of the @{b}--help@{ub} option. @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-q@{ub}, @{b}--quiet@{ub} @{lindent 3}
Specifying this once does nothing since @{b}xzdec@{ub} never displays any warnings or notices. Specify this twice to suppress errors. @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-Q@{ub}, @{b}--no-warn@{ub} @{lindent 3}
Ignored for @{"@{b}xz@{ub}(1)" link %s.%sxz1/main} compatibility. @{b}xzdec@{ub} never uses the exit status @{b}2@{ub}. @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-h@{ub}, @{b}--help@{ub} @{lindent 3}
Display a help message and exit successfully. @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-V@{ub}, @{b}--version@{ub} @{lindent 3}
Display the version number of @{b}xzdec@{ub} and liblzma. @{lindent 0}


@endnode

@node sect4 "Exit Status"


· @{b}0@{ub} @{lindent 3}
All was good. @{lindent 0}

· @{b}1@{ub} @{lindent 3}
An error occurred. @{lindent 0}

@{b}xzdec@{ub} doesn't have any warning messages like @{"@{b}xz@{ub}(1)" link %s.%sxz1/main} has, thus the exit status @{b}2@{ub} is not used by @{b}xzdec@{ub}. 


@endnode

@node sect5 "Notes"
@{b}xzdec@{ub} and @{b}lzmadec@{ub} are not really that small. The size can be reduced further by dropping features from liblzma at compile time, but that shouldn't usually be done for executables distributed in typical non-embedded operating system distributions. If you need a truly small @{b}.xz@{ub} decompressor, consider using XZ Embedded. 
@endnode

@node sect6 "See Also"
@{"@{b}xz@{ub}(1)" link %s.%sxz1/main} XZ Embedded: <http://tukaani.org/xz/embedded.html> 


@endnode
